  

<h2 id="what-to-do-when-pretty-headers-become-visual-clutter">What to do when pretty headers become visual clutter</h2>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/0620c607-98cc-4540-b845-fa63a1555674/affinity-percent202026-01-05-percent2008-19-49.png" alt="Screenshot of a todo.txt file. Tasks have dates ranging from 2014 to 2017" width="1406" height="860"></p>
<p>I came across some of my very first plain text files recently while looking for something else.</p>
<p>What an awwwwww moment!</p>
<p>It was like seeing early photos of your offspring by chance and realising just how much they have grown. My text-babies were born around 2014 and they are so cute in their level-1 simplicity! I love how supremely readable they are, despite the rookie errors. (I was an old-school graphic designer with no non-GUI experience, and had just briefly heard about Markdown)</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/c96dc087-d005-471a-89bc-f95108f56488/cleanshot-percent202026-01-05-percent20at-percent2.png" alt="screenshot of a .txt file showing improper use of Markdown (no space between hashes and text, header text with bold styling)" width="1912" height="1162"></p>
<p>The sweet and simple look of the raw Markdown in those files has inspired me to make changes to to the look of the files Iâ€™m using today. Iâ€™ve switched to a monospaced font for both reading and edit views, and removed the colour and size variations for different header levels via the Minimal Theme Settings and Style Settings plugins.</p>
<h3 id="embracing-a-variety-of-ways-to-simplify">Embracing a variety of ways to&nbsp;simplify</h3>
<p>Cute as all that colour and font detail was, I was starting to find each one the equivalent of a tap on the shoulder. Or the eyeballs. Itâ€™s no exaggeration to say that my brain could come up with something to be distracted by in a silent, empty room with no windows! I appreciate all the help I can get to stay on task.</p>
<p>If you can relate to this but like me you still crave variety, try cycling through a couple of sets of fairly plain options. Your aim is to get a subtle new look without opening up Pandoraâ€™s Box of Tweaking Temptations.</p>
<p>The following four variations of the same text illustrate the point. Each pings different parts of my brain, and Iâ€™m grateful it is quick and easy to switch between them without leaving the comfortable boundary of plain text files.</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>Obsidian Minimal theme:</li>
</ol>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/4bae0faf-94cd-441a-9e68-6371c63669e4/ptpl-189-ob-colour.png" alt="Text with three levels of headings, each a different size and colour" width="1148" height="863"></p>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li>MarkEdit:</li>
</ol>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/c9bed87e-6423-4b66-97a0-e70aedcb8278/ptpl-189-markedit.png" alt="Text with three levels of headings of descending sizes, all of which are blue" width="983" height="863"></p>
<ol start="3" type="1">
<li>Obsidian Minimal theme, colour removed via Style Settings plugin:</li>
