<p>(Did your eagle eye pick up that there are two <em>betweens</em> in each text sample? Mine didnâ€™t, until Iâ€™d finished writing this and noticed the blue underline in the TextEdit version. I also noticed that Iâ€™d neglected to add blank line paragraph spaces, but that didnâ€™t show up in any but the TextEdit version)</p>
<h3 id="defining-the-scope-of-your-files">Defining the scope of your files</h3>
<p>Where are the boundaries of your files and your workflow? Are you just as clear on what doesnâ€™t belong, as on what does?</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/07251e6e-a5bb-4366-90df-7bdc5d33f947/ptpl-189-calendar-txt.png" alt="a block of text in calendar.txt format" width="1704" height="1384"></p>
<p>When I started the calendar.txt tiny experiment, the file was, as per the protocol, a wall of text. As time went on I began including journal-type entries along with the events, but that quickly got out of handâ€”even with syntax highlighting.</p>
<p>I had to define what the file was actually <em>for</em>, and make decisions on what did not belong there. In the case of the plain text calendar, a format shakeup was also needed.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn.blot.im/blog_177bc256f0ee469c998e912e20ece048/_image_cache/3593ce57-1e7c-49b8-a56e-be190f0416e8/pasted-percent20image-percent2020260105090851.png" alt="screenshot of Obsidian window showing an outline in the right sidebar and text under date headings in the main section. The outline shows year, month, week, and daily headers in descending levels" width="2440" height="1596"></p>
<p><a href="https://ellanew.com/2025/09/29/ptpl-175-calendar-txt-simplest-time-planning-system" title="wikilink">Calendar.txt</a> is now planner.md, and has a Markdown header hierarchy and blank lines between each section. The previous version was a cool idea and it worked, to an extent, but I came to see that that kind of rigidity wasnâ€™t serving me.</p>
<p>The blank lines in my planner file now provide visual differentiation between sections when scrolling through the days, without distracting my brain the way sizes and colours used to.</p>
<p>(I love how easy Obsidian makes this kind of shakeup! Using the Style Settings plugin I can change things up very quickly. And that plugin allows downloading settings so you can save and reload old sets at will.)</p>
<p>Principle: Define the scope of your document. What does it need to do? What are you choosing <em>not</em> to have the document do? For example:</p>
<p><strong><span class="small-caps">IN</span> <span class="small-caps">SCOPE</span></strong><br>
My planner file must show me what I have committed to do on specific dates in the future, and allow space for time blocking and non-negotiable tasks.</p>
<p><strong><span class="small-caps">OUT</span> <span class="small-caps">OF</span> <span class="small-caps">SCOPE</span></strong><br>
Someday or maybes do not belong here. If a task or event is in my planner, it happens! â€” Or it gets rescheduled. No transclusions, no embedded search queries!</p>
<p>I hope that the planner file case study helps to illustrate that the thinking behind a workflow matters more than the tool or system being used. And that is something which can be applied to any need, style, or taste.</p>
<h3 id="take-aways">Take aways</h3>
<ul>
<li>Define your scope and stick with it; modify as needed</li>
<li>Be aware of the things that distract you and reduce them by adjusting the way you use your tools</li>
<li>Things that are unnecessary but which make you smile are okay too but make sure your system works without them</li>
<li>Be intentional with everything you layer onto and around the basics</li>
</ul>
